answer_en:
You may have sleep apnea syndrome (SAS). It is recommended that you seek medical attention at an early stage. SAS is a disease that negatively affects your health. It is recommended that you visit a specialized clinic (such as a sleep outpatient clinic) for diagnosis and receive necessary treatment.
In general, you may also be able to improve your bedtime breathing by:
- Avoiding alcohol or smoking before going to bed;
- Avoiding drinking a lot of water or using sleeping pills before going to bed;
- Changing your sleeping position, such as adding a cushion or pillow to your side and sleeping on your side;
- Cleaning room air and maintaining adequate humidity (using a humidifier or opening windows for ventilation);
- Using an over-the-counter nasal breathing support medication for relieving body congestion at bedtime; and
- Trying nasal breathing and training oral muscles on a daily basis, in addition to measures at bedtime.

medicalRiskNote_en:
- Using an over-the-counter nasal breathing support medication for relieving body congestion at bedtime;
=> Relieving nasal congestion?
=> “Nasal breathing support medication” may be an error? (Not an over-the-counter medicine)
